column168: Company driver was discharging Sodium Hydroxide 50% from the cargo tank into customer's bulk storage tank. The bulk storage tank reached full capacity prior to the cargo tank becoming empty. The customer's employee closed the inlet valve to the bulk storage tank. The driver began depressurization of the cargo tank so that the discharge hose could be disconnected from the cargo tank and bulk storage tank. The driver failed to allow full depressurization of the cargo tank prior to disconnecting the discharge hose and subsequently released approximately 5 gallons (64 pounds).
column169: The driver will be retrained using the Bulk Shipments Standard Operating Procedure which includes guidelines for emptying discharge lines and confirming that receiving vessels can accept a load in its entirety.    Additionally, better coordination between the driver and the customer should prevent reccurence of this event.

column168: At 6:45AM Monday December 6, 2010, during the daily facility security inspection an employee noticed that one of the rail cars on the storage track (leased track) was leaking.  He immediately called management on his radio.  The material is Magnesium Bisulfite, and is customer – owned.  We immediately called the owner of the car to notify them and request their assistance with the incident.  They then dispatched a truck to assist with the control of the leak.  At the same time Univar Operations Management and Regulatory Management were contacted as well as the local emergency responders.  Fire Dept and Hazmat teams arrived at 7:30AM.  They did not participate in the control of the incident, but they did stay in case things got worse or any injuries occurred.  In order to minimize the loss of product, we inserted a spill pallet directly on the tracks under where the product was leaking.  We then parked the customer’s tanker near the rail car and used their pump to transfer the material from the containment to their truck.  At that point we brought in 2 more customer tankers and pumped product directly from the rail car to the tankers until the rail car was empty.  In order to determine the amount of the spill, we weighed each truck light and heavy.  By calculating difference between what was loaded onto trucks and the original weight of the rail car, it was determined that approximately 90,000 lbs of product was released from the car.  The Fresno County Dept of Environmental Health Services has been notified of this, and they have contacted the State Water Quality Board.  The customer (TKI) has contacted a remediation contractor and will be working with them and the County DEHS directly.

column168: During a routine yard check at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a trailer was noticed to have a leak coming from the nose of the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The 300 gallon tote tank loaded in the nose of the trailer was found to have leaked from the valve, which appeared to be broken.  The affected area on the ground was covered with boom and absorbent material to keep the material in containment.  The tank was completely emptied from the leak.  The tank was taken out of service and sent to a reconditioner for repair.  The cleanup materials were placed into a suitable salvage container and disposed of.  The trailer was deconned with a cleaning compound and placed back in service.
column169: The trailer had been loaded 2 hours prior to the discovery of the leak.  The temperature at the time was 20 degrees.  The impact of the tote tank against the trailer wall may have caused the outer cage to flex, allowing contact with the valve.  The cold may have affected the area where the poly tank connected with the valve, causing a crack which resulted in the leak.  All loading personnel were instructed to use more care in loading these containers against trailer walls to insure there willbe no movement between packages during transportation.

column168: On 12/08/2010 at 11:49 hrs., CSX personnel in Dothan, Alabama discovered UTLX 200862, a residue tank car of Alcohol, N.O.S, leaking from the bottom outlet valve cap. The car was isolated and the shipper, Murex N.A. Ltd., the NRC - report 961702, Alabama EMA, and CHEMTREC - report 2010-12-08-00096, were notified. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet cap less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ms. Dowd 972-934-2901. Eagle/SWS drained the secondary valve, inspected the gasket, properly tightened the bottom outlet cap and cleaned up the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A 7.1 QA Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause code: 149  NARRI: 5(4+3+0) X (2+0) = 70

column17: United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc.
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery, a leak from the vent cap resulted in the release of approximately 15 gallons of diesel fuel.  The free product released to the asphalt surface within the lot, and traveled into a nearby storm drain.  Environmental Services, Inc. of South Windsor, Connecticut responded to assist in cleanup, which involved the application of absorbent material to the asphalt surface, which was recovered and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  United Industrial Services of Meriden, Connecticut was dispatched to washout the affected storm drain.  United Industrial Services inspected the outfall, which provided no evidence of diesel fuel.  Free product was contained within the storm drain catch basin, which was flushed, generating approximately 198 gallons of wash water.  Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations, and site was deemed for closure.  No further action remains.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the incident.
column169: United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Driver was making delivery of a portable tank of perchloroethylene (Iso-form) to the “stores” area of the plant.  When driver opened trailer door and looked at the tank he noticed a small drip coming from the discharge valve area.  He checked the valve handle and it seemed to be turned all of the way to the closed position.  The driver then placed absorbent materials under and around the leaking area. A field technician was immediately sent to the site to secure the leak. The field tech secured the absorbent pads around the leaking area and underneath the tank then followed the driver back to the Brisbane plant.  There was only a small amount of product that leaked out of the tank (<2 lbs) and all of it was contained with the absorbent materials.    This tank is fitted with a customer provided dry-break disconnect fitting.  The tank was inspected by Brisbane maintenance and it was found the reason for the leakage was the orientation of the valve was such that when the handle was turned to the open position it was not perfectly horizontal causing it to be at an angle when open.  This caused the handle to come into contact with the dry-break disconnect fittings not allowing the valve to open all of the way.  Customer personnel had bent the valve handle up to where it would clear the fittings allowing the valve to open, but when the valve was closed the handle was hitting on the underside of the tank preventing the valve from closing all of the way. The dry-break disconnect fitting had a defective Teflon O-ring which allowed the product to leak out.  The orientation of the valve was corrected, the handle bent back to the proper position and the O-ring replaced with a new one.  The tank, valve and dry-break were pressure tested and placed back into service.
column169: Upon return of all tanks for filling, maintenance will inspect the orientation of the valve to ensure it is in the proper position.

column168: An inbound mechanical inspection in the railyard revealed UTLX 200343 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with fresh product on its side shell which was evaporating. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder with contract responders inspected UTLX 200343 and reported finding UTLX 200343's manway gasket missing. A new Nitrile manway gasket was applied and all manway securement bolts were tool tightened. Spillage on the side shell that hadn't evaporated was wiped and no ground spillage was observed. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact shipper seal Suncor Energy 193627 was replaced with seal TIS 5900. No further product release was reported from UTLX 200343 during subsequent rail movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: COFC shipment - load was billed to JBH as non-hazardous on the EDI transmission.  JBH driver was given non-hazardous shipping papers.  Load was in-gated to BNSF intermodal facility as a non-hazardous load.  Upon arrival in CA, the load was discovered to have been loaded with 500 lbs of class 8 hazardous materials.      Internal investigation revealed the load was not offered to JBH as a hazmat load.  The most likely root cause of the incident lay with a shipper employee not fully understanding or inadequately trained to fully understand the 1001 lbs exception regulations.  500 lbs total of class 8 hazardous materials were shipped (not requiring placards); the hazmat employee who placed the order  for the shipper seems to have not realized that hazardous shipping paper, declaration, blocking & bracing, etc regulations still fully apply under the 1001 lbs exception contained in 49 CFR 172.504.  Consequently, 500 lbs of hazardous materials was not declared to JBH when the load was offered and the issue was not discovered until the cargo had nearly arrived at its final destination.    Timeline given below:    On 12/11 @ 12:48pm, JBH drivers arrived at customer to recover JBHU 249173 that had been preloaded for transport via rail from Alliance to Stockton.    • JBH driver noticed there were flammable placards on the container and that the bills had the word “HAZMAT” in a particular section.  • JB Hunt driver approached the shipping office to request the MSDS sheets so that he could do his hazmat briefing with local dispatch.  • The person on duty ( driver did not get a name ) at that point, advised the driver that there was no hazmat on the container and they went out to the yard and removed the placards themselves, stating that the container had previously come in as an inbound load with hazmat on it, and they had just forgotten to remove the placards.  • Since the container was already sealed, the driver had no reason to really question what they were telling him.  • At 1500 hrs driver arrived at the Alliance rail yard to in-gate the unit and edi billing was transmitted as non-hazardous.  • On 12/14 @ 04:49 the Stockton crew grounded this unit from the train and notified JBI that it was ready for transport to customer in Sacramento, CA.  • Based off the scheduled delivery appointment provided by our customer, We arrived a driver at the Stockton rail yard on 12/15 @ 00:11 hrs.  • Due to the nature of most of the commodity that we haul for this customer, we sent in a hazmat certified driver to pull the container. While doing his pre-trip inspection and preparing to call in for his hazmat briefing, he discovered that there were no placards on the unit, nor was there any hazmat bills. Driver then aborted his assignment and a request was sent to JB Hunt Corporate to obtain them so delivery could be made.  • 12/15 @ 06:30, local operations was questioned why they needed hazmat bills if the load was non-hazardous. It was then determined by documentation th
column169: Internal investigation satisfied JBH Safety the shipper does not systematically fail to disclose hazardous materials when offered; this appears to have been an isolated incident.  JBH safeties recommendation has been to offer additional hazardous materials training to our partner shipper.  JBH is satisfied the shipper has been very receptive to our offer to receive additional hazardous materials training.  JBH load & ride solutions will also provide the shipper with additional training and support to meet all blocking & bracing requirements of DOT/FRA and of JBH’s partner rail carriers.  JBH and our partner carriers will increase random inspections of loads originating from the shipper, with a particular emphasis on loads containing exception quantities of hazardous materials to ensure these are being properly secured.

column168: At about 1100 on 12/8/2010 a tanker carrying hazardous waste, shipped under UN 1993 with methanol and sulfuric acid, was involved in a roll over.  The incident occurred in a construction zone, where trucks were diverted onto a temporary roadway.  Pictures taken at the scene seem to indicate that the roadway literally crumbled beneath the semi-truck's tires.  NOTE - SEVERAL incidents have occurred in the same construction zone and the fire department repeatedly asked for the closure of that portion of roadway.  Following notification, Ross Transportation faxed shipment information to the Ohio State Highway Patrol, the scene was stabilized by Kingsville Fire, Plymouth Fire, Ashtabula HAZ MAT and Ohio State Highway Patrol.  Emergency responders, tow-trucks and clean-up contractors were dispatched to the scene.  The roll-over caused a breach in the tractor's fuel tanks and less than 170 gallons of diesel was released and less than 1 pint of hazardous waste shipment was released from the tanker all of it caught in the manhole well.  A construction worker dug three holes to catch the diesel fuel being released.  Then as the tow truck operator slowly uprighted the tanker, the shipment was transferred into a vac tanker.  Once all material had been transferred, the vac tanker vacuumed up the diesel and the holes were stuffed with absorbant.  The absorbant was removed 24 hours later and so signs of diesel remained. The vac tanker and clean-up crew finished up around 7PM when the roadway was reopened.
column169: Company drivers have been told to avoid the area until roadway construction is complete.

column168: On 12/7/2010 at 11:15 hrs., Joseph Bowen, NJ DOT Inspector, was inspecting cars in the CSXT Manville yard in Manville, NJ, and discovered PTLX 126020, a residue tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids N.O.S., Manifest 408629VES, with a vapor leak from the manway of the car. The car was isolated and the consignee, Veolia ES Technical Solutions, was contacted. Veolia ES Technical Solutions sent a representative to inspect the leak and they discovered a defective manway gasket and 1 of 8 manway bolts less than tool tight. Veolia ES Technical Solutions personnel replaced the manway gasket and the leak stopped. The tank car was secured and released for transport.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 209  NARRI: 5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

Summit Environmental, the shipper's emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the BOV cap was not tool tight. column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shippers location to Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in  Bristol, CT for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste  management facility. While transferring one container, it was discovered that approximately 8 ounces of material escaped from the bottom of the  container. Facility personnel placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. All required local and state reports were made that included verbal reports to the Connecticut  Department of Environmental Protection and local Fire Department.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: A tanker truck had been loaded with DAF wastewater and was being weighed at the gate of the generator.  The driver, making a routine inspection of the vehicle during that time, noticed a small leak coming from the vent line of the tanker.  A response crew was summoned who donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the leaked material.  The clean up material was placed into a suitable salvage container and taken back into the plant for later shipment.  The cause of the leak was a frozen vent line that did not properly seal.  The line was thawed out, re-sealed properly, and the load continued to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver was cautioned to insure that all vent lines are properly closed during sub freezing temperatures.

column168: Transporter's Driver backed onto concrete pad in front of loading tanks. Shipper's Operator came and hooked up the loading hose, opened the valves and open the top dome of the tanker. Operator then started pumping the liquid into the Transporter's tanker.Shipper's Operator stood outside the drivers cab and ask the Driver to check the air suspension gauge in the tractor.Driver stated the gauge was at the half way level.After 5 min., Operator ask Driver what the level was at, and it was still reading half way. So Driver got out of tractor, just as material started to spill out over the dome and down the overflow pipe to the concrete pad. Operator shut down the pump and called for a vacuum truck to vacuum up the 5 gallons that had spilled. Driver moved tanker to the on site scale. Air gauge was reading heavy at 80300 pounds.Driver went back to have material vacuum out of the trailer -3400 pounds. Outside temps were -10 degrees.
column169: Facility operator should know number of gallons pumped per minute and -approximate time needed to fill tanker. Driver should be watching gauges closer for any problems.

column168: Please note, Schenker, Inc. shall be named as reporting party only. According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While unloading, one (1) cardboard box, which contained four (4) plastic 3.78 liter bottles, was discovered damaged. Apparently, one (1) plastic 3.78 liter bottle had been punctured, which resulted in the release of approximately 1.89 liters. The product had released inside its original cardboard box, and contaminated the adjacent cardboard boxes within the shipment. Boston Scientific was contacted to discuss response actions. Reliant Cargo Services of Miami was contracted by Boston Scientific to assist in repackaging freight, and containment of the contaminated cardboard. Reliant Cargo Services responded,repackaged the contaminated freight, containerized contaminated cardboard, and sent remaining shipment on to the consignee. Reliant Cargo Services took all waste generated during cleanup, pending proper disposal. One (1) cardboard box, which contained four (4) plastic 3.78 liter bottles was held in OS&D, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Schenker, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all dock personnel.

While switching GATX 23381 at Pasadena Yard on 12-19-2010 at approximately 1700 hrs PTRA train crew 236 smelled a foul odor. They reported the smell to the yardmaster and trainmaster on duty. Investigation found that the GATX car was leaking from the manway area when the car was moved back and forth. Lubrizol was contacted and sent a responder. Randall Wilson from Lubrizol arrived at 1830 hrs. He opened the manway cover and discovered that the gasket was pinched and torn on the edge closest to the manway hinge. He replaced the gasket and sealed the car. No product was observed on the ground it was on the sides of the tank car and evaporated before contacting the area around the car.
column169: PTRA has requested that Lubrizol investigate the cause and provide a solution to the problem and prevention action steps.

column168: After repairing the leak on GATX 23381 (see report# E2010120328) PTRA train crew reported a similar odor while switching NATX 72732 at approximately 2000 hrs. PTRA Director of Safety was on scene at the time and confirmed the presence of the odor. NATX 72732 and GATX 23381 was set over the a track where they could be inspected further.  Lubrizol was notified and sent a responder out to investigate. It was determined that the vaccuum relief valve had been operated improperly and was stuck in the open position. The responder reset the valve and determined that it did not need to be replaced and was operating properly.
column169: PTRA has requested an action plan to prevent future incidents from Lubrizol.

column168: Driver had connected his product hose the trailer and the customer receiving line.  The operator requested another bottom sample prior to product transfer. The driver started to open the trailer valves to allow material to flow to his blow down fitting for sampling. The driver changed his mind thinking that he didn't want to dirty his hose in the event the material was rejected. He closed the trailer valve and disconnected his hose. Driver than slowly opened the internal valve but forgot that he had not closed the external valve. The product spilled into the containment structure before he could close the internal valve. Driver cleaned up and there were no issues with the plant.
column169: Driver error he obviously was distracted or in a hurry and did not focus on what he was doing.  Driver will be disciplined as outlined in the company disciplinary policy.

Entrained NAHX 2965 (AAR C711, two compartment covered hopper) struck a failed drawbar that broke off of a railcar entrained ahead of NAHX 2965 during train movement. The fallen drawbar component struck the underside of NAHX 2965 causing a small puncture hole at the A-end forward facing bottom outlet hopper slope sheet. This puncture hole allowed product to spill out during movement and continued until the BNSF train was stopped on main track to investigate the emergency brake application that followed. Contract responders applied a temporary patch to the slope sheet hole stopping further product release. The spillage trail and the spillage underneath NAHX 2965 (where NAHX 2965 came to rest) was shoveled into super sacks and later returned to the shipper. A small amount of spillage (estimated at less than one gallon) sifted through the openings of a bridge structure into a creek below. Water samples were taken at the creek site with no recordable product contamination found.      FRA verbal emergency movement approval FRA-101202V was granted to move the temporarily repaired and still entrained NAHX 2965 to the next BNSF railyard location (Memphis, TN) for possible product transfer activities and furtherance. Later, FRA-10120834 was subsequently granted to supersede the verbal movement approval. NAHX 2965 arrived at the BNSF Memphis railyard without further incident.  NAHX 2965 was reinspected at the BNSF Memphis railyard and contract responders applied an overlaid patch atop the temporary patch on the slope sheet to ensure no further product release from this hole during subsequent movement of NAHX 2965 back to the shipper. FRA-10120834-Revision 1 was granted for this movement and NAHX 2965 arrived at the shipper location without further incident.

column169: BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS! RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING  PRESHI FT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column169: THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DANNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT ON BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE COMPLETELY SECURELD BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: December 17, 2010: While performing a joint routine hazmat inspection in Conrail's South Philadelphia, PA Greenwich Yard, FRA Chief Inspector J. Moore and CR Risk Manager A. Richter noted product on tank car GATX 16358, containing the residue of Ferric Choride, Solution.  Product puddled on manway nozzle mounting plate, and had also contacted all valves and fittings mounted thereon.  Additionally, wet product staining noted on both sides of the car down to the drip ledges on both sides of the car, but had not contacted the ground under the car.  This car had been recently switched from the shipper, Savage Flexi Flo Terminal, Philadelphia, PA, on 12/16/10 at 2021 hours.    CR contacted REACT Environmental Services to assist with clean up, and FRA contacted shipper, Savage Industries Flexi Flo, Oregon Avenue, Philadelphia, PA, who also responded.  Further inspection noted all valves and fittings were adequately secured.  Product residue was reported by Savage Flexi Flo representative W. Davis to have been result of the product line being disconnected after the last unloading of this car at his facility.  Facility procedures for cleaning the car prior to offering the car for transportation were not followed.    Product reside on manway nozzle mounting plate, and all other effected fittings, was wiped clean using chemical absorbant pads.  Car okayed for shipment to original destination.

column169: USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR BAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFELY TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: ON 10 DECEMBER 2010, A UPS DRIVER SERVICE PROVIDER PICKED UP A PACKAGE FROM THE SHIPPER'S ADDRESS SHOWN IN THIS REPORT.  THE PACKAGE WAS MARKED AS UNIVERSAL WASTE CONTAINING MERCURY.  AT 15:45 WITH THE PACKAGE CAR (VEHICLE NO. 136586) BACK AT THE BLUE GRASS DELIVERY CENTER, EMPLOYEES DETECTED MERCURY LEAKAGE IN THE VEHICLE AND REPORTED IT TO MANAGEMENT.  AN OUTSIDE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY AND ENGAGED TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  THE CONTRACTOR WAS ON THE SCENE WITHIN AN HOUR AND DETERMINED THE SOURCE PACKAGE AND IDENTIFIED THE CONTAMINATION THAT HAD AFFECTED SEVERAL OF THE 170 PACKAGES IN THE VEHICLE.  THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGE CONSISTED OF AN OVERPACKED 5-GAL PAIL, CONTAINING A VAPOR-LOCK LINER WHICH HELD AN UNDETERMINED NUMBER OF MANUFACTURED ARTICLES CONTAINING MERCURY.  BOTH THE LINER AND LID HAD FAILED.  THE CONTRACTOR COLLECTED REMOVABLE CONTAMINATION AND TOWED THE VEHICLE TO ITS FACILITY FOR COMPLETE EVALUATION AND CLEAN-UP.  THE VEHICLE WAS CLEANED UP BY 12 DECEMBER.  JUST OVER 2 LB OF MERCURY WAS REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE.  A TOTAL OF 36 PACKAGES WERE CONTAMINATED AND REQUIRED DISPOSAL OR REPACKING.
column169: THE SHIPPER NEEDS TO PAY CLOSE ATTENTION TO CLOSURE OF BOTH LINER AND PAIL TO PREVENT MERCURY SPILLS.  ALSO, THE SHIPPER MUST FOLLOW THE PUBLISHED LAMP TRACKER INSTRUCTIONS TO LIMIT ELEMENTAL MERCURY CONTENT TO UNDER 1 LB.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While travelling near 20516 State Road 69 in Blountstown, Florida, the valve on the portable tank broke. Eagle/SWS of Panama City, Florida was dispatched to perform the remainder of the cleanup.  Eagle/SWS applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted roadway and excavated the contaminated soil from the impacted area.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However Davis Supply, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: An unattended BNSF train parked on main track awaiting a replacement train crew was reported by a passing BNSF signal maintainer (whom stopped to inspect train after smelling product odor emanating from the area where train was parked) that entrained TILX 315662 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was leaking product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). The maintainer reported that the bottom operated BOV handle was not pinned and in the open position; and its bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) was not applied. The maintainer repositioned the BOV operating handle to the closed position, ending the product release. The BOC was then applied and tightened.   Afterwards, BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected TILX 315662 and ensured the BOV and BOC were properly secured. Inspection of product outage inside TILX 315662 indicated that TILX 315662 was mostly empty. Environmental contractors vacuumed spillage that had migrated into a track-side ditch that had some standing water. Recovered liquid (product/water mix) was stored onsite in a portable Frac tank for content sampling and future disposal. The main track was inspected from the spill site back to Emporia, KS (approx. 13 miles) with no product spillage noted. Soil sampling and ground remediation at the spill site is on-going.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 12/12/2010 at approx. 18:38 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Aaca Yard in Richmond, VA, discovered AMOX 13211, a loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten, leaking vapors from the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, BP Products, was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2010-12-12-0056. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found vapors coming from the manway. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Jerry Zimmer 847-963-9220. HEPACO discovered the manway gasket was misaligned and corroded. HEPACO personnel replaced the gasket with like in kind and secured the car for transportation. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. Shipper/Carrier employee was offloading product from an IBC when he noticed a leak in the area behind the valve.  A drip pan was in place to catch the material leaking.  The employee continued tranferring product to customer tank in order to minimize the amount leaking.  When the consignee's tanks (2 @ 245 gallons) were full there was still approximately 20-30 gallons left in the tote that overflowed the drip pan and leaked onto the ground.  A consignee employee and the shipper/carrier driver cleaned up the spilled material.
column169: Shipper/carrier employees were informed of this incident during periodic safety meetings.  Shipper/carrier employees perform a pre-fill inspection on each hazardous material container, including examining the valve.  The container did not leak during the filling, storage or transportation of the IBC. Subsequent investigation revealed that a number of container's valve threads were cross-threaded. It is likely that the weight of the hose and product on the cross-threaded valve during product transfer resulted in the leak.  Shipper/carrier employees have received additional training to specifically look for valves that do not appear to be square with the IBC or may be otherwise compromised.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver was delivering ULSD to a customer location. While unloading the driver noticed the gauges on the tank were not moving. While unlaoding the driver noticed gas leaking from the top of tank 2. He again, immediately stopped the flow of prodcut but approximately 150 gallons leaked into the containment area. The spill was completely comtained and cleaned by site personnel. Upon investigation it was determined that the guages were linked to a computer system that monitered overfill alarms as well and none was operating.

column168: A BNSF road switch crew in the railyard reported product leaking from the manway area of UTLX 211051 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car). column168: On 12/31/2010 at 17:54 hrs., personnel at the CSXT Big Four Yard in Russell, KY discovered UTLX 130312, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking liquid and vapors from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper, Bayer Material Science, was notified via CHEMTREC, Report 2010-12-31-00096. Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the gasket between the fill hole nozzle and the fill hole cover was out of place on one side. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Chad Blake 412-777-7475. Quick Response replaced the gasket and secured the fill hole bolts with a wrench. The leak stopped and the car was released for transport.    This incident did require a special switch move.   QA 7.1 Non conformance report will not be required for this incident    Cause Code: 232  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: INTX 8027 (AAR C113, 4 compartment covered hopper) was delivered to the consignee's industry track on Saturday afternoon, 12/18/2010. On Monday, 12/20/2010, the consignee notified BNSF that employees arriving to work noticed a product pile under the B-end bottom hopper outlet. The consignee reported that the B-end bottom outlet's discharge door track was clogged with product/dirt which prevented the full closure of this bottom discharge door and subsequent spillage of product from this partially open bottom outlet. The shipper seal was intact on this bottom outlet. The bottom outlet door track was cleaned and the bottom outlet closed. The consignee cleaned the ground spillage at the site and recovered product to be recycled for reuse by the consignee. A BNSF environmental contractor inspected the BNSF St. Joseph railyard finding several small piles of ammonium nitrate pellets that were presumed deposited by INTX 8027 when it traveled in the railyard on 12/18/2010. The contractor collected the spillage found in the railyard and placed this recovered product in recovery drums which were delivered to the consignee for their recycled reuse.

column168: A FRA-Rail Safety Inspector-Hazardous Material inspected several railcars that were recently pulled by BNSF from the shipper's facility. The FRA Inspector reported finding CTCX 780179 (DOT 112J340W tank car) with a product odor when the valve housing cover was opened for valve inspection. Further detailed inspection revealed the sample line valve and its closure plug iced over from product release. The sample line valve's T-handle was not in the full closed position. Nearby shipper responders were summoned and the sample line valve was closed. Afterwards, shipper responders checked all valve securement on CTCX 780179 finding all secure. Securement was completed by 1115 hrs. MST, 12/22/2010.

column168: Two bags travelled with passenger from inbound from Boston connecting in Miami going to Kingston.  Upon arrival in Miami at 11:31 am and during offload, one of the bag was taken from jetveyor and dropped two feet into the ground which exploded upon impact.  All government agencies responded.  The bomb squad searched and cleared both bags.  The second bag was found to contain a bag full of primers which didn't detonate.  The first bag had 700 primers that exploded. column168: GATX 200271 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) staged for unloading on an ACTA (Alameda Corridor Transportation Authority) storage track was reported dripping product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). A local UPRR hazardous material responder inspected GATX 200271 and reported that the bottom operated BOV operating handle was not in the fully closed position nor was it pinned and sealed. Also, the bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) was found not tool tight. The responder moved the BOV operating handle to the closed position and pinned it. The BOC was tool tightened. Afterwards, product dripping ceased. All spillage evaporated with no evidence of ground impact observed.

column168: -NO PACKAGE FAILURE, RELEASE    12-13-10    Approximately 8AM on 12-13-10, Federated Co-ops, Inc. petroleum delivery employee Charles Immel was traveling around 50 miles per hour going west on Chisago County Road 19 west of Stacy about a mile. It was calm, sunny and 4 degrees with a clear frozen road but not covered and compacted with snow. Charles then saw a car approaching him fishtailing. It seemed to gain control only to start fishtailing again. He stayed in his lane and tried to pull over to the right slightly as the car lost control and collided with our truck. AS it slid to the left into the oncoming lane, it hit the truck in the drivers fron bumper and left quarter with right side.    The momentum of the loaded truck (1000 gallons of gas and 3500 gallons of fuel oil) then pushed the car an estimted 100-150 feet into the ditch. Both vehicles remained upright and no fires or leaking of fuels occurred. The Minnesota duty officer ws called.     There was a witness named Erick Dewey 763-250-8345, saw the whole thing. He was driving a handicapped van with clients in there so couldn't stay but called with his information to the investigators. He even called Mora and JIm Gutzwiller with his information and said our driver couldn't of done anymore.    Charles was uninjured and seemed to be ok. The driver of the car was unresponsive and died it is thought instantly. The body was removed from the car at 10:19AM. The driver of the Suburban that took the body away returned to the scene and I overheard him say that "the driver may have had a heart condition, they need to see her medical records." That may of lead to the incident. Her I.D. is not yet known, as is her insurance information.    Chisago County Sheriff Department will be doing the accident report; the State Patrol did the accident reconstruction with its case numbe MN00RA000561. By 1PM we completed pumping the truck's contents into another of our trucks brought to the scene by Rod Hamann, then it was pulled out of the ditch and taken to Dan's Towing in Forest Lake where it went through a DOT Inspection by Technical Sergeant Micheal Wayne #188) phone 651-405-6197. It will then be taken to Determan Brownie in MInneapolis immediately following. The tank has little or no damage. Chassis damage remains to be scene but looks to be in grave condition.     Officers say all of our vehicle paperwork was in good order. There were no hints of the incident being our fault whatsoever from anyone. Federated employees other than Charles at the scene were Petroleum Division Manager and Charle's supervisor Brian Devries (phone 763-238-2846), Rom Rausch, Safety Director (phone 763-286-2299). and Rod Hamann the driver of the other fuel truck. Charles said the officers on the scene gave him an alcohol breath test, Tom took Charles to the Osceola Medical Center for the DOT post-accident urine drug test. After the test was completed Tom and Charles had lunch and then Tom took Charles to his home in North Branch.

column168: Clancy’s Transfer and Storage, Inc. was hired to move non-hazmat items.  Clancy's was briefed not to move hazmat items.  Instructions were given to transport the items located in a connex box excluding hazardous materials.  Upon receipt of the shipment at the destination location, a hazardous material was recognized as an item that should not have been transported.  The item was a 72 inch long, 2 inch in diameter cylinder for He-3, manufactured by GE Reuter Stokes.  The cylinder did not have any markings that would indicate that it contained a hazardous material.  The only markings on the cylinder were non-DOT manufacturer markings (i.e., RS P4-1672-207) and a serial number (i.e., 03D59769).  There was no release of material.  Upon identification the incident was reported using the Pacific Northwest National Laboratory Event Reporting Procedure.

column168: EXHIBIT A:    At 0930, MDDE conductor Jason Yeatman reported a stong smell of propane emanating from an 8-car cut of loaded propane tank cars (Hazardous placard 1075) while conducting switching operations at the runaroud track in Federalsburg, Maryland. At the time of the incident, weather conditions were partly cloudy skies and an air temperature of 30 degrees with winds out of the north at 10 to 20 mph. Mr. Yeatman halted all operations and informed the engineer of the train, Randall Rash, of the situation. Mr. Rash shut down the train's sole locomotive and informed MDDE's Federalsburg Office of the smell. The Federalsburg Office immediately notified MDDE President Eric Callaway, MDDE Assistant General Manager Scott Harris and Earl Slacomb at Tri-Gas & Oil, the consignee from whom all of the loaded propane railcars were consigned. Mr. Harris arrived on the scene at 0947 and was met by Lieutenant Edgell from the Federalsburg Fire Department who worked at E S Steel, an industry adjacent to the Federalsburg runaround track. Mr. Yeatman had notified the industry of the leak and E S Steel hAd suspened all operations and welding. E S Welding did not do any evacuations.      Upon checking car HOMX 180173, Lieutenant Edgell discovered a leak on the top of the car, evidenced by ice and frost that was covering tow valves, as well as the sound of escaping air and the strong smell of propane from the hatch. At 0958, Tri-Gas & Oil representatives Earl Slacomb and Joe Capello arrived and inspected the top of car HOMX 180173 with Mr. Harris and Lieutenant Edgell. The seal was still on the car and all parites agreed that the car did not appear to have been tampered with. Mr. Capello brokE the seal on the hatch to reveal two vavles heavily frosted over and loose. Mr. Capellos retrieved a pipe wrench and began tightening both valves. After each vaLVe was tight, the frost was brushed off and the valves were soap tested for leaks. All parties agreed that the leak has been stopped and Mr. Cappello then closed and secured the hatch.    At 1017, Mr. Harris notified Lisa Matsinger at FRA and briefed her on the vents that unfolded. No injuries or evacuations resulted from the leaking railcar. Shortly after 1020, Mr. Capellos re-sealed the railcar and Mr. Rash re-fired the locomotive on the train and the train crew continued switching operations. At 1228, car HOMX 180173 was  placed for unloading in Williamsburg, Md, at tower 8 on Tri-Gas & Oil rail siding. Tri-Gas immediately began the process of unloading the car in addition to the other seven (7) placed in their siding.

column168: KCS car men found the car to be leaking during the initial inspection.   Isolate the car in zone 5 track 22 for response.  Hulcher Environmental Services was mobilized for response. Responder found loose packing gland on valve stem. The packing was tightened stopping the release.  To facilitate response, removed seals Air Liquide 0870835 and 0870836. These seals were replaced with seal numbers are 2692074 and 2692075.    KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.    Report Notes:  Item 27, amount in package, was estimated by preparer. This action was to facilitate data acceptance by defective DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required for two reasons:   (1)because the shipper only provided bulk quantity on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements; and   (2)because the DOT e-system requires data in this field which use the same units of measure as found in the capacity field.   KCS will continue to report in this fashion unit instructed differently by DOT or PHMSA.    Report Notes:  Item 26a, package markings, didn't provide selection for proper DOT specifications. The DOT specification for this package is 204W. The DOT electronic system forces data to be entered in this field. Therefore to make DOT accept this report data other than 204W was entered.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NAR's are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NAR's.

column168: CAUSE OF THE RELEASE: THE OPERATOR OF THE TRUCK-TRAILER LOADING THE OIL DOZED OFF WHILE FILLING THE PULL TRAILER (TRAILER NUMBER 2). THE CENTRIFUGAL LOADING PUMP CONTINUED TO TRANSFER CRUDE OIL AND THE TANK SUBSEQUENTLY OVERFILLED AND RELEASED OIL THE CONCRETE PAD ON WHICH THE TRUCK-TRAILER TEST PERFORMED ON THE PULL TRAILER WAS ON 11/29/10 AND THE PULL TRAILER CONSTRUCTION DATE WAS NOVEMBER OF 1994.  CONTRIBUTING SOURCE OF INFORMATION: DALE STRIETER, PATRIOT; SCOTT MCGOWAN AND DAVE PALMER, PAN PACIFIC PETROLEUM.    THE CALCULATED RELEASE TOTAL WAS APPROXIMATELY 50 BARRELS. THIS WAS DETERMINED FROM READINGS ON THE DISCHARGE LEASE AUTOMATIC  CUSTODY TRANSFER (LACT) METER. METER START FIGURE WAS 0 BARRELS, METER END FIGURE WAS 260 BARRELS, MINUS THE EXISTING CONTENTS OF THE TRAILERS (WITNESSED BY DFG-OSPR) OF 211 BARRELS, EQUALS APPROXIMATELY 49 BARRELS. THIS QUANITFICATION WAS PERFORMED BY CALIFORNIA  DEPARTMENT OF FISH AND GAME-OFFICE OF SPILL PREVENTION AND RESPONSE (OSPR) OIL SPILL PREVENTION SPECIALIST ED BOYES IN CONCURRENCE WITH SCOTT MCGOWAN OF PAN PACIFIC.   CONTRIBUTING SOURCE OF INFORMATION: DALE STIETER, PATRIOT; ED BOYES, DFG-OSPR; SCOTT MCGOWAN, PAN PACIFIC    NO PRE-EXISTING SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURES WERE IN PLACE.   CONTRIBUTING SOURCE OF INFORMATION: DALE STRIETER, PATRIOT; DALE SKEEN, BREITBURN ENERGY    THE PATHWAY OF MIGRATION OF THE RELEASE FROM ITS SOURCE (PLEASE SEE PATHWAY MAP IN ATTACHMENT 3): OIL OVERFLOWED FROM THE PULL TRAILER AND IMPACTED THE CONCRETE PAD ON WHICH THE TRUCK WAS PARKED. IT FLOWED OFF THE PAD TO THE LEASE SOUTH FENCE LINE, UNDER THE FENCE TO A DEPRESSION IN THE SOIL. THIS DEPRESSION LED WEST TO THE DRIVEWAY OF THE FACILITY. UPON REACHING THE DRIVEWAY, THE OIL FLOWED SOUTH TO THE GUTTER OF EAST 7TH STREET. THE OIL THEN FLOWED EAST TO THE STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN ON THE NORTH SIDE OF 7TH STREET AND ENTERED A STORM DRAIN CULVERT. THE OIL THEN FLOWED SOUTH UNDER 7TH STREET AND ENTERED THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM UNDER THE CITY OF LONG BEACH RECREATION PARK 9-HOLE GOLF COURSE. THE OIL CONTINUED TO FLOW SOUTH UNDER THE GOLD COURSE UNTIL IT MET A DEPRESSION ("BELLY") AND DEBRIS IN THE STORM DRAIN APPROXIMATELY 300 FEET NORTH OF THE 6TH STREET ENTRANCE TO COLORADO LAGOON. THIS OBSTRUCTION CAUSED THE OIL TO BECOME TRAPPED AT THIS POINT. NO OIL WS DETECTED TO HAVE MIGRATED BEYOND THIS POINT AND COLORADO LAGOON WAS NOT IMPACTED.   CONTRIBUTING SOURCE OF INFORMATION: DALE STRIETER, PATRIOT; ROBERT WISE, US EPA    QUANTITY THAT REACHED A NAVIGABLE WATER: NONE. QUANTITY THAT REACHED THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM: APPROXIMATELY 1 BARREL. THIS WS DETERMINED DURING QUANTIFICATION PERFOMED BY OSPR IN CONCURRENCE WITH SCOTT MCGOWAN OF PAN PACIFIC. QUANTIFICATION CONSISTED OF OIL THICKNESS OBSERVATION AND STRAPPING CHART MEASUREMENT IN EACH OF THE FOUR 500 BARREL TEMPORARY STORAGE TANKS THAT CONTAINED THE RESIDUALS OF CLEANING THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM FROM 7TH STREET TO THE END OF THE SYSTEM.  CONTRIBUTING SOURCE OF INFORMATION: DAL
column169: ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT THE RELEASE FROM REACHING ANY NAVIGABLE WATERS PER THE INCIDENT ACTION PLAN(S):  AT THE RELEASE LOCATION: DRIVER AND LATER BREITBURN LEASE PERSONNEL SHOVELED NEARBY SOIL TO CREATE A BERM TO STOP THE GROSS PRODUCT FLOW. 12/2/10 AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HRS. APROXIMATELY 2 BARRELS CONTAINED BY THIS ACTION. column169: USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR BAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFELY TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGING MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLCOKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS; KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! column168: THE LOADING OPERATION BEGAN AT 10:40 AM ON 12-02-2010 AND DISCONTINUED FLOW AT 11:12 AM. THE CAMLOCK FITTING ATTACHING THE LOADING HOSE TO RAILCAR ACFX 200214  FAILED ALLOWING A PORTION OF THE LOADING FLOW TO BE RELEASED. IMMEDIATELY UPON DETECTION OF THE RELEASE, FLOW TO THE LOADING PUMP WAS DISCONTINUED AND THE RELEASE WAS TOPPED. MOMENTIVE DETERMINED THE RELEASE TO BE IN EXCESS OF A REPORTABLE QUANTITY AT APPORXIMATELY 12:55 PM BASED UPON THE APPROXIMATE SPILL DIMENSIONS.     FORMALDEHDE THICKENS AT AMBIENT CONDITIONS. VISIBLE FORMALDEHYDE WAS IMMEDIATELY RECOVERED. LIQUID AND WASH DOWN WATER FROM THE SPILL WAS ALSO RECOVERED AND WILL BE REUSED ON-SITE IN THE PRODUCTION OF FORMALDEHYDE. AS A PROTECTIVE MEASURE, THE VISIBLE FORMALDEHYDE AND TOP TWO INCHES OF SOIL FROM THE SPILL LOCATION HAVE BEEN EXCAVATED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT A OFF SITE WASTE TREATMENT FACILITY IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE REGULATORY REQUIREMENTS.    AN EXAMINATION OF THE CAMLOCK FITTING ON THE LOADING HOSE INDICTATED THAT THE LOCKING RING ON ONE EAR OF THE FITTING HAD BECOME DEFORMED AND FAILED. THE PREVENTED THE EAR FROM COMPLETELY LOCKING IN PLACE. AFTER LOADING BEGAN, THE CONNECTION FAILED AND A PORTION OF THE FLOW WAS RELEASED OUTSIDE CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE LOADING DOCK.
column169: THE LAODING HOSE AT ISSUE WAS A NEW HOSE THAT HAD ACTUALLY BEEN REPLACED EARLIER THIS YEAR ON 6-10-2010. MOMENTIVE HAS HAD NO LOADING ISSUES WITH THIS EQUIPMENT UNTIL THIS EVENT.    ALL CHEMICAL TRANSFERS AT THE GEISMAR FACILITY WHERE CONNECTIONS ARE USED WILL NOW REQUIRE THE USE OF A VELCRO STRAP OF EQUIVALENT PROTECTION DEVICE AS A SECONDARY MEANS OF PREVENTING FAILURES.    THE OPERATING PROCEDURES AND CHECKLIST HAVE BEEN REVISED TO REQUIRE THE USE OF THE VELCRO STRAP. ALL OPERATIONS STAFF HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED OF THIS REQUIREMENT.

column168: Dear Mr. Scott:    CCS, A division of PNE Corp. was contracted by Wilcox and Flegel Oil Company to provide response services and mitigation to a gasoline spill involving an overturned tank truck on Hwy 30 near Deer Island, OR. The incident occurred on December 31st , 2010 and CCS was notified at approximately 2125 and asked to respond with resources.    Background:  A fuel tanker operated by Wilcox and Flegel was transporting fuel northbouNd to Hwy 30 during the evening of December 31st, 2010. The truck struck cows which had wandred on to the roadway, the resulting accident ended with the truck being overturned while the trailer unit remained upright and connected. ODOT and Columbia River Fire and Rescue (CRFR) closed Hwy 30 in both directions until the accident could be cleared and when safe to do so. Wilcox and Flegel requested CCS resources to contain the spill and mitigate further impact from Gasoline into the environment.     Response:  CCS arrived on-site at approximately 10:45 in the evening and met with Wilcox and Flegel and the Incident Commander from CRFR. An initial plan was developed to perform reconnaissance of the scene to determine appropriate strategies. The gasoline tanker was noted to be releasing 5 gallons per minute from each of two locations on the tanker. The first on the driver side of the tank, this leak was emanating from a tear in the aluminum tank. The second leak was from the strong back hatch cover on the forward compartment.     CCS evaluted strategies for containment and recovery of remaining fuel in the tank, it was determined that the best and most effective method would be to drill the tanker allowing access to each of the two compartments. A vacuum truck was standing by to receive gasoline. CCS performed a safety briefing with all personnel and outlined the operational plan for fuel access and removal. It ws determined that the scne was not safe for operations due to the presence of gasoline on the ground surface and unimpeded leaking of gasoline. CCS requested that CRFR place foam over the impacted area prior to entry operations. When the foam was in-place, CCS Began with setting up operations for the drilling.    CCS utilized a nitrogen supplied air drill and a 3" hole saw for drilling the tanker. Grounding and bonding lines were setup and the equipment and setup was analyzed prior to drilling. CCS placed a containment pool underneath the forward leaking hatch while drilling the rear compaRtment. Once the rear compartment wAs drilled, CCS then drilled the forward compartment and removed remaining fuel. All fuel remaining in the compartments were removed totaling 3,072 gallons. CCS then began with assisting in the offloading of contents in the trailer (Diesel fuel) to Wilcox provided trucks.     Once all fuel was removed and contained in transport vehicles, CCS demobilized from the site and established a time to regroup on-site for additional mitigation measures. A utility locate was ordered prior to demobiliza

column168: SEQUENCE OF EVENTS: THE IBC WAS PICKED UP ON DEC. 15, 2010.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN PARKED FROM DEC. 15 TO DEC. 20, 2010.  ON DEC. 20, 2010 THE TRAILER WAS DRIVEN TO THE DESTINATION, N. 9246 HWY 80 S IN NECEDAH, WI.  THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO UNLOAD THE IBC AND DISCOVERED THE RELEASED MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.                                                                                                 ACTIONS TAKEN:  THE DRIVER CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AND THEN CALLED THE CARRIER (LAKEVILLE MOTOR EXPRESS) AND REPORTED THE RELEASE.  THE DRIVER INFORMED THE BUSINESS OWNER OF THE RELEASE.  THE BUSINESS OWNER HAD ACCESS TO A SKID-STEER AND SAND AND WAS ABLE TO PLACE THE SAND ON THE RELEASED PRODUCT ON THE DRIVEWAY TO PREVENT FURTHER MIGRATION OF THE MATERIAL. THE CARRIER CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC., AN  EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY FOR THE CARRIER, AND ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITES.  THE CLEANUP CREW USED CLAY ABSORBENTS TO REMOVE THE RELEASED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND FROM THE DRIVEWAY UNDER THE TRAILER.  THE CONTAMINATED ABOSRBENTS WERE COLLECTED AND STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CONTAMINATED SAND WAS COLLECTED AND STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CREW ALSO TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE IBC INTO THREE DRUMS.  THE THREE DRUMS WERE SENT FOR RE-USE.  A STORM DRAIN WAS IMPACTED BY THE RELEASED PRODUCT AND WAS FLUSHED BY THE CLEANUP CREW.  THE RINSE WATER WAS ALSO COLLECTED, STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.  ALL WASTE FROM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITES HAS BEEN SENT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  PACKAGE FAILURE: THE TOP OF THE IBC WAS BROKEN IN SEVERAL PIECES.  THE RESULTING HOLE OR OPENING WAS APPROXIMATELY 24 INCHES BY 24 INCHES.                                                                                        CAUSE OF FAILURE: THE PRODCUT INSIDE THE IBC FROZE FROM COLD WEATHER AUSING A LAYER OF ICE TO FORM ON THE TOP OF THE PRODUCT.  THE ICE LAYER MOVED DURING TRANSPORTATION AND STRUCK THE INSIDE OF THE IBC.  THE STRIKING OF THE ICE BROKE THROUGHT THE TOP OF THE IBC, CAUSING THE RELEASE.  THE TOP OF THE IBC MAY HAVE BEEN BRITTLE FROM PREVIOUS REPEATED EXPOSURE TO THE SUN.                                                                  PHOTOGRAPH ATTACHED.

column168: A BNSF train which was stopped on main track received a roll-by inspection from a passing BNSF train. This inspection revealed entrained BOCX 3012 (AAR 204W tank car) was venting Argon from its side operating compartment/cabinet. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was dispatched (from Amarillo, TX) to the site. The responder's inspection revealed the interior cabinet was frosted or iced over. The liquid line valve was found partially open (1/2 inch turn to fully close) and liquid was dripping from around this line's dust cap or closure cap. Responder deduced that the wire tie down applied did not prevent vibration from opening the wheeled valve handle. The responder closed the valve which ended the venting and adjusted the tie down wire after the valve was closed. Intact shipper seal 8907903 was replaced by seal numbered 802464. Response concluded by 1340hrs. CST, 12/19/2010.

column168: While en-route to location fellow employees notice that a metal tote carrying Mineral oil had moved on the trailer. They stop driver in a pull out areaalong CO 330/65. A decision from the home office was to send out a third party with fork-lift to set tote properly back on trailer. Fork-Lift operator slide the forks underneath the tote to reposition the mineral oil and punctured the other tote on the opposite side. Immediately hands took the damage tote off the trailer and position it to stop leaking. Chemical ran less than 3 minutes spilling approx 125 gallons. BJ hands place absorbents on ground and damn up the liquid so it would not run into a local river next to the road.  A CDOT employee arrived on scene and declared he was in control and did not want BJ to finish transferring and removing the spill. With all of the proper documentation and information provided he would not listen and declared the roadway be shut down. At this time Plateau Valley Fire department arrived and the  HazMat and Colorado State patrol called. 3 hours later the HazMat team showed arrived because they had not been dispatched initially. Plan was talked about how BJ was going to transfer the remaining chemical with the Hazmat captain and that a state recogized emergency response group called ECO was coming to finish with the remediation and Clean up. He agreed too it and stated to the CDOT employee BJ knew what they were doing and left. CDOT employee did not stay around either and left. BJ proceeded with chemical clean up and turned it over to ECO when they arrived. ECO nuetralized and removed contaminated soil and wash pavement.

column168: I DID MAKE A WIDE TURN, ENTERING TO THE GAS STATION, WHEN A SMALL CAR WAS LIVING. (DRAW #1). PER INSTINCT, I DID CLOSE MY TURN TO LEFT, TO AVOID THE CAR ON MY WAY. FORUTNATELY THE OTHER CAR MAKE THE SAME, TURNING LEFT AND LIVING BY THE CAR-WASH PATH. (DRAW #2).     FROM MY POSITION, I START BACKING-UP TO RECOVERY SPACE TO ENTER TO THE DROPS. WHEN I DID CHECK BY THE DRIVER SIDE MIRROR I WAS SAYING TO STOP SIGN ONLY, NOT THE OTHER IRON POLE IN ANGLE BEHIND THE SIGN. THAT POLE SCRATCH THE TANK BUT IN SOME INSTANT, IT MAKE A PERFORATION IN THE WALL OF COMPARTMENT #3, STARTING THE S        PILL. (DRAW #3).    I DID TRY TO CONTENT THE SPILL, BUT I CAN'T BECAUSE THE POLE WAS INSIDE THE HOLE, ALSO I WAS REMOVED FROM THE RISK AREA BY THE POLICE....    WHEN THE FIRE DEPT. CAME, WE CORRDINATE TO MOVE FORWARD THE TRUCK TO THE UNDERGROUND TANKS AREA AND DROP THE GAS FROM THE DAMAGED COMPARTMENT AS SOON AS POSSIBLE TO STOP THE SPILL...    SUPERVISOR AND 911 SERVICE WERE CALLED AT TIME OF THE INCIDENT....
column169: WE IMMEDIATELY BECAME A CLIENT OF EAGLE SWG AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. ALL DRIVER ARE AWARE OF THE PROCESS AND WHEN TO CALL. WE REEVALUATED OUR MATERIALS ON THE TANKER MAKING SURE EVERYTHING IS IN PERFECT CONDITION. WE HAD AN IMMEDIATE SAFETY MEETING TO EMPHASIZE THAT WE ARE DEALING WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND THE IMPORTANCE OF SAFETY.

column168: Summary for incident at (-95 mile marker 263 below:   Tractor-Trailer with 240 gal combined saddle-tank capacity with estimated 175 Gal diesel carried at time of impact, struck concrete barricades protecting median of 1-95 overpass under construction, while south-bound on 1-95; resulting in diesel fuel-spill 30- 60 yards long onto the inside “break-down lane” and shoulder. This runoff did not flow anywhere. The trailer was initially allowed to burn to consume HazMat. This appears to have worked, consuming the Polymaleic Acid and Tolyltriazole. We can identify only melted remains of their (assumed) poly drums. Litmus air and soil/water testing has not identified any acidic areas, reading Alkili, when any reading detected. The four (4) 55gal metal drums of Gear Lube are bulging, but intact, with only minor seepage from bungs. The 1,271 pounds of Herbicide have not yet been identified. If the 2.5 gal containers were plastic, that may explain why.   TLI has contracted HazMatl for cleanup (subcontracting with EagleSWS). John Lucarelli (Eagle SWS, 407-854-5733, cell 407-702-8910) is on-scene, Initiating cleanup operations.

column168: The Medium Service transfer had been shut down by the driver and the spill was contained.  Approximately 5-7 gallons of Molten Sulfur impacted the asphalt as a result of the product hose violently shaking as the truck was emptying out.  The cam locked ears on the product hose detached and allowed a mix of sulfur and air pressure to escape the hose.
column169: The driver is responsible for controlling the air compressor in this medium service transfer.     ROOT CAUSE:  1. It was determined that the air regulator, which is controlled by the driver, had been altered and was reading 50psi when the Work Instructions stated that the carrier would not exceed 40psi.      CORRECTIVE ACTION:   1. A locking shroud was purchased and installed to prevent drivers from tampering with the regulator and increasing the psi.

column168: JOHN WAS DRIVING ON RIGHT LANE EAST BOUND ON 1604 AFTER PASSING THE STONE OAK EXIT HE IS COMING UP THE HILL AND THAT IS WHEN HE NOTICE THE VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM HIT THE BRAKES. JOHN HAD APPROXIMATE-150 FT DISTANCE AND HE STARTED PUMPING HIS BRAKES AS WELL, THIS IS WHEN THE TRUCK STARTED TO SLIP/LOOSE TRACTION AND HE COULD NOT GAIN CONTROL. THIS IS WHEN THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRUCK COLLIDES INTO A GREEN HONDA THAT WAS ON THE LEFT LANE. AT THIS POINT HE IS STILL TRYING TO GAIN CONTROL AND ENDS UP HITTING THE CONCRETE DIVIDER IN THE MIDDLE OF THE HIGHWAY. THIS IS WHEN THE TRUCK FLIPPED ON TO THE DRIVER SIDE AND CONTINUED TO SLIDE APPROXIMATELY 40 FT FINALLY COMING TO A STOP. AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY JUMPED OUT THE TRUCK THROUGH THE PASSENGER DOOR. DRIVER CALLED YANTIS SHOP TO REPORT INCIDENT. AROUND 1:20PM FERNANDO FIGUEROA (SAFETY MANAGER/HAZMAT CERTIFIED FOR YANTIS) ARRIVED ON SEEN. THE FIRE DEPT. WAS ALREADY ON SITE CONTROLLING MAJORITY OF SPILL AND PUMPING FUEL FROM THE TRUCK INTO 55 GAL DRUMS (4). POLICE DEPTS. HAD CLOSED 1604 FROM BLANCO TO AFTER THE 281 EXIT. FERNANDO AND RICK SAUCEDO (FROST INSURANCE SAFETY REP.) DROPPED SOAK BOOMS IMMEDIATELY BEFORE DRAINAGE AREA TO CONTROL SPILL AND ALSO AROUND THE AREA WERE NEEDED. FROM THERE FERNANDO CONTACTED CALLED OUR OTHER FUEL TRUCK DRIVER MARK MARTINEZ TO ARRIVE AT SEEN WITH OUR FUEL TRUCK (FT-4) AND WE PUMPED THE 1255 GAL. LEFT OF THE RED DIESEL FUEL ON THE WRECKED TRUCK INTO OUR FT-4 FUEL TRUCK. WE ALSO CONTACTED BAGLE SWS TO COME AND CONDUCT THE HAZMAT CLEANUP, THEY ARRIVED ON SITE SHORTLY AFTER OUR FUEL TRUCK DRIVER AND IMMEDIATELY STARTED WITH THE CLEANUP AND VACUUM SUCTION OF ALL FUEL AND WATER AROUND DRAINAGE AREA. THIS PROCESS CONTINUED UNTIL THE STREET AND OTHER IMPACTED AREAS WERE CONTROLLED AND CONTAINED. ONCE THE WRECKED FUEL TRUCK WAS EMPTY WE HAD TX TOWING USE THERE EQUIPMENT TO FLIP OUR TRUCK AND LOADED ON TO OUR LOWBOY, WHICH WE COORDINATED TO ARRIVE ON SITE TO TRANSFER WRECKED TRUCK TO OUR YARD. A FEW HOURS AFTER THE HIGHWAY WAS OPENED APPROXIMATELY 10:00PM.

WHEN THE WEATHER CONDITIONS ARE NOT IN OUR FAVOR THE SAFETY MANAGER OR YOUR SUPERVISOR WILL EMAIL AND CALL ALL DRIVER PERSONAL TO ACTIVATE THE BAD WEATHER POLICY
